            "title": "The development of human resource management across nations : unity and diversity",
            "abstract": [
                "The development of human resource management across nations : history and its lessons for international and comparative HRM / Bruce E. Kaufman -- A century of human resource management in Argentina / Carlos Aldao-Zapiola -- Human resource management in Australia : historical development and contemporary tensions / Christopher Wright -- The historical evolution of human resource management in Brazil / Zil\u00e1 Guimar\u00e3\u0303es Horta -- The evolution of human resource management in China : traditions, reforms and developments / Xiangquan Zeng, Liwen Chen, Zhongxing Su -- The history of human resource management in France / Jacques Rojot -- The history of human resource management in Germany / Ruth Rosenberger -- The evolution of human resource management in the UK / Howard Gospel -- Human resource management in India / J.S. Sodhi -- The historical development of human resource management in Israel / Itzhak Harpaz -- The evolution of human resource management in Italy : an historical-institutional perspective / Giovanni Costa and Arnaldo Camuffo -- The evolution of human resource management in Japan : continuity, change, and enduring challenges / Jong-Won Woo -- The development of human resource management in South Korea / Young-Myon Lee -- Human resource management in Russia over a century of storm and turmoil : a tale of unrealized dreams / Igor Gurkov, Evgeny Morgunov, Alexander Settles, and Olga Zelenova -- Human resource management in the Republic of South Africa / Marius Meyer -- Employment regimes and personnel work in Sweden / Lena Gon\u00e4s and Patrik Larsson -- Human resource management in Turkey / Lale T\u00fcz\u00fcner -- The origins, evolution, and current status of human resource management in the United States / Bruce E. Kaufman",
                "\"This volume contains country studies of the historical development of human resource management (HRM) in seventeen different nations. The nations span all regions of the world and each chapter is written by a national expert. Primary attention is given to HRM developments in industry, but university research and teaching are also covered. Human resource management is defined broadly to include industrial relations and each chapter places the historical development of HRM in a broad political, social, and economic context.\"--Publisher's website"
